'''Bilistiche''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: Βιλιστίχη<ref>'''Belistiche''' in Pausanias; '''Belestiche''' in Plutarch; '''Blistichis''' in Clement (''Protrepticus'' 4.42); '''Philistaikhus''' in Eusebius (''Chronikon''); '''Bilistiche''' in pCairZen 2.59289.</ref>) or '''Belistiche''' was a [[Hellenistic]] [[courtesan]] of uncertain origin. According to [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], she was a [[Ancient Macedonians|Macedonian]];<ref name = "Pausanias">[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]]. ''Description of Greece'', 5.8.11. "Later they added a pair of foals and a ridden foal: they say Belistiche, a woman from the coast of Macedonia, won with the pair, and Tlepolemos the Lykian was proclaimed for the ridden foal, Tlepolemos at the hundred and thirty-first Olympics and Belistiche two games before."</ref> according to [[Athenaeus]], an [[Argead Dynasty|Argive]] (which was an ancient Greek royal house and the ruling dynasty of [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedon]]);<ref>Athenaeus. ''Deipnosophists'', 13.596e.</ref> according to [[Plutarch]], a foreign slave bought from the marketplace.<ref>Plutarch. ''Moralia'', 753e.</ref> She won the [[Chariot racing|tethrippon]] and [[synoris]] horse races in the 264 BC [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympic Games]].<ref name = "Pausanias"/> She became a mistress of [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus]] and was deified by him as Aphrodite Bilistiche.<ref>{{harvnb|Pomeroy|1990|pp=53–55}}; {{harvnb|Golden|2008|pp=18–19}}.</ref> According to [[Clement of Alexandria]], she was buried under the shrine of [[Sarapis]] in [[Alexandria]].<ref>Clement of Alexandria. ''Protrepticus'', 4.48.2-3.</ref>
